Bnonymous !!iJ/aThauPsd Thu 25 Aug 2022 01:41:14 No.50419495 Report
Quoted By: >>50419665
>>50419205
I don't have a lot to offer on this subject, unfortunately. The most I can point towards is mass information and content with regards to the ease of entry for the internet and technology in general.

Without the internet, and the world in general being rather secular, anime was rare, and anime furry stuff even rarer, so we didn't get much from Japan besides Sonic and Star Fox. Most of the time, the best place to find furry characters was Don Bluth films, and those were family friendly. Most of us didn't consider the implications of fucking the characters. But most millennial furries and fur-appreciators can trace their appreciation back to either Sonic, Star Fox, or Don Bluth.

With constant connection of internet and greater bandwidth potential, things like scanners, digital cameras and later tablets began to get popular, and more things spread that way. Communities formed and began to talk, popularized more things, made their own culture, which also spread virally.

Honestly most I remember about back then was the isolation. Furry shit was underground, and when I say underground I mean fucking molepeople underground. If you didn't know the right people, you didn't know shit unless you stumbled across it randomly. The dial up days are when any real grouping started, IRC chatrooms, ancient forums and whatever could be hosted on shit in a garage. If you're spoiled by anything it's how well connected online sites are now, google grew into a megacorp for a reason, the search engine changed everything when it went online. It's probably a truly alien concept but try imagining how much harder finding ANYTHING online was then.

No google, no search engines, no nothing. Just random hidden sites, geocity pages, webcomics, artist sites, and more. Everything was word of mouth and naturally kept discreet for the most part when it came to furry because 7/10 times it was porn.
